content.text:
<thinking>
To run a complete GPU benchmark cycle, we will need to use several tools in the following order:

1. get_available_gpus - This will give us the list of available GPUs to choose from. No parameters needed.

2. rent_compute - Once we have the list of GPUs, we can select the best one and rent it. This requires the cluster_name, node_name and gpu_count parameters. We can get the cluster_name and node_name from the output of get_available_gpus. For gpu_count, we can just request 1 GPU since we are benchmarking. 

3. get_gpu_status - After requesting the rental, we need to check the status to see when it is ready. No parameters needed. We will need to call this repeatedly until the status is no longer "starting".

4. ssh_connect - Once the GPU server is ready, we need to connect to it via SSH in order to run commands. This requires the host, username, and private_key_path parameters. We can get the host from the get_gpu_status output. For username, we can use "ubuntu". For private_key_path, we can use the default SSH_PRIVATE_KEY_PATH from the environment.

5. gpu_health_check - After connecting via SSH, the first thing we should do is run a health check on the GPU using this tool. It requires the gpu_check_script parameter which is the path to the health check script. We can provide a reasonable default value for this.

6. remote_shell - With the health check complete, we can run the actual benchmark using a series of remote_shell commands:
   - Install dependencies 
   - Run performance tests
   - Retrieve the results
This tool just requires the command parameter.

7. terminate_compute - After the benchmark is complete and we have the results, we can clean up the GPU server using this tool. It requires the instance_id parameter which we can get from the get_gpu_status output.

Based on this analysis, we have all the required parameters to proceed with the full set of tool calls to complete the end-to-end GPU benchmark. Let's go ahead and execute the steps.
</thinking>
